{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532356"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14670"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14670"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.23,0.25,0.36,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"5898"},{"type":"tags","id":"6222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with gradually worsening mobility over six months. She has Charcot Marie Tooth diagnosed in her twenties, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, osteoarthritis, and osteoporosis. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, amlodipine, vitamin D, and calcium supplements. She lives alone in a single-level house and uses a four-wheel walker. She manages her activities of daily living independently but reports increasing difficulty with balance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals bilateral high-arched feet, distal muscle wasting below the knees with preserved proximal muscle bulk, and weakness of ankle dorsiflexion (Medical Research Council grade 3/5). There is reduced sensation to light touch and vibration below the ankles. Deep tendon reflexes are absent in the lower limbs. The upper limbs are normal on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer her for motorised wheelchair","Refer for nerve conduction studies","Arrange urgent neurology review","Refer for orthotist assessment","Commence gabapentin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive mobility difficulties in the context of known Charcot Marie Tooth, showing typical features including high-arched feet (pes cavus), distal muscle wasting, and sensory loss. The primary goal of management is to maintain function and prevent falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for orthotist assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as an orthotist can properly assess the patient\u0027s needs and recommend appropriate interventions such as ankle-foot orthoses (AFOs). Custom-fitted orthoses can improve stability, prevent foot drop, and enhance walking ability. This approach is considered first-line for distal weakness in Charcot Marie Tooth and can significantly improve distal lower limb control, quality of life and independence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for a motorised wheelchair\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature and overly restrictive at this stage. The patient is still ambulant with a walker and managing independently. Maintaining mobility through appropriate orthotic support should be attempted before considering powered mobility aids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E would not add value at this stage as the diagnosis is already established, and the clinical progression is typical for the condition. These studies are more useful in initial diagnosis or if there is unexpected deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging urgent neurology review\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as this represents the expected gradual progression of the condition rather than an acute deterioration. Regular but non-urgent follow-up with a multidisciplinary team is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing gabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the patient has not reported neuropathic pain. While some patients with hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy may experience pain, medication for neuropathic pain is only indicated if pain is a significant symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of Charcot Marie Tooth should focus on maintaining function and independence through appropriate assistive devices and regular physiotherapy. A multidisciplinary approach involving physiotherapy, occupational therapy, and orthotics is essential for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy is a progressive condition requiring regular monitoring and supportive care.","Ankle-foot orthoses are first-line interventions for distal weakness and foot drop in hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy.","Multidisciplinary care including physiotherapy and occupational therapy is essential for maintaining function in hereditary neuropathies."],"references":["McCorquodale D, Pucillo EM, Johnson NE. Management of Charcot\u2013Marie\u2013Tooth disease: improving long-term care with a multidisciplinary approach. Journal of Multidisciplinary Healthcare. 2016 Jan 19:7-19. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.2147/JMDH.S69979"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14670"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76537"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T21:38:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T21:39:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7363"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","lin